**Update** the first solution is accepted, but it's not accurate. See the second solution below.

Why this problem is marked hard?

We traverse the tree and return INT_MIN if it is not BST. Otherwise, we return the sum of its node values.

If sums for the both left and right subtrees is not INT_MIN (both subtrees are BST), we then check if the value of the current node is greater then left node value, and lower than right node value. If it is, we return the sum of the entire subtree.

Otherwise, return INT_MIN.

```cpp
int maxSum = 0;
int dfs(TreeNode* n) {
    if (n == nullptr) return 0;
    auto ls = dfs(n->left), rs = dfs(n->right);
    if (ls != INT_MIN && rs != INT_MIN) {
        if ((n->left == nullptr || n->left->val < n->val) 
            && (n->right == nullptr || n->right->val > n->val)) {
            maxSum = max(maxSum, n->val + ls + rs);
            return n->val + ls + rs;
        }
    }
    return INT_MIN;
}
int maxSumBST(TreeNode* root) {
    dfs(root);
    return maxSum;
}
```

**Updated Solution**
The solution above is accepted, however, as [hiepit](https://leetcode.com/hiepit/) and [MohammedShoaib](https://leetcode.com/mohammedshoaib/) pointed out, it produces wrong result for use case like this: `[4,2,6,1,5,3,9]`. To address it, we need to also track the minimum and maximum value of the subtree, and check that the node value is greater than the maximum, and less than the minimum of left and right subtrees, respectfully.

So, instead of just sum, below we return tree values: {sum, min value, max value}.
