# Final Optimal Solution

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f2dc9222-2289-4c11-9587-375b2369f9a5_1638006460.8124442.png)

```java
public class MaxSumBSTinBTOptimal {
    int maxsum = 0;
    public int maxSumBST(TreeNode root) {
        postorder(root);
        return maxsum;
    }

    private int[] postorder(TreeNode root) {
        if(root == null)
            return new int[]{Integer.MAX_VALUE, Integer.MIN_VALUE, 0}; // {min, max, sum}

        // postorder -> Left Right Root
        int[] leftTree = postorder(root.left);
        int[] rightTree = postorder(root.right);

        if(leftTree == null ||
                rightTree == null ||
                root.val <= leftTree[1] ||
                root.val >= rightTree[0]
        ) {
            return null;
        }

        int sum = root.val + leftTree[2] + rightTree[2];
        maxsum = Math.max(maxsum, sum);

        int max = Math.max(root.val, rightTree[1]);
        int min = Math.min(root.val, leftTree[0]);

        return new int[]{min, max, sum};
    }
}
```

**Explanation**
In this solution we do a postorder traversal which is (Left -> Right -> Root) 

Step by step definition of algorithm goes as follow:-
- the array which is returned from postorder function contains 3 values, minimum from right subtree, maximum from left subtree, and sum of nodes in tree.

```java
if(leftTree == null ||
		rightTree == null ||
		root.val <= leftTree[1] ||
		root.val >= rightTree[0]
) {
	return null;
}
```
- This says that if either left subtree is not bst or right subtree is not a bst or root.val is less than maximum of left tree or greater than min from right then return null.

- Then we calculate sum, min and max along with updating maxsum.
- then we return an array containing all 3.

