solutions.content:
Write an auxiliary function to recursively check if a tree rooted with node `r` is a BST, if it is, return True and the sum of the tree at the same time. Every time you get a valid tree sum, append it to the `res`.

Please note that in this problem, null nodes connected to the leaf nodes can also be considered as a valid node/subtree with sum 0. So example 3 returns 0 instead of any negative node.

```py
class Solution:
    def isBST(self, r):
        if not r:
            return True, 0
        is_left, left_sum = self.isBST(r.left)
        is_right, right_sum = self.isBST(r.right)
        if (r.left and r.left.val >= r.val) or (r.right and r.right.val <= r.val):
            return False, 0
        if is_left and is_right:
            s = left_sum + right_sum + r.val
            self.res.append(s)
            return True, s
        return False, 0

    def maxSumBST(self, root: TreeNode) -> int:
        self.res = []
        self.isBST(root)
        if self.res:
            return max(max(self.res), 0)
        else:
            return 0
```

