# Intuition
Basic recursion.
We cant go to every node and and check for binary tree. The constains are very high, hence we need to go in one traversal and check for binary seach tree and calculate sum.

Now at a node, we say it is bst only if it is greater than left and less than the right.
Now to check for left and right first and then the root.
We can do a postorder traversal.
Left-->Right-->Root

# Approach
Now for postorder, lets say at leaf node, they are always a bst in themselves 
when we get null, we return min value as INT_MAX and max value as INT_MIN. So when it gets at leaf it satisfiy for bst.
now at evety node we just check for bst 

if BST-->we take sum of both left , right and root.
```
int sum=root->val+lt.sum+rt.sum;
return BST(sum,min(root->val,lt.mini),max(root->val,rt.maxi));
```

if not BST-->we just take max of left and right as the current root doesnt form the bst.
so we just pass on the earlier max value of sub-BST.
```
return BST(max(lt.sum,rt.sum),INT_MIN,INT_MAX);
```

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
We just traverse the tree once and hence TC-> O(N)

- Space complexity:
We use another data structure BST
which take O(1) space but stack space is used
Hence O(H) where H is height of tree

# Code
```
class BST {
public:
    int sum;
    int mini;
    int maxi;
    BST(int sum=0,int mini=INT_MAX,int maxi=INT_MIN) {
        this->sum=sum;
        this->mini=mini;
        this->maxi=maxi;
    }
};
int ans=0;
BST helper(TreeNode *root) {
    if(!root)return BST(0,INT_MAX,INT_MIN);
    auto lt=helper(root->left);
    auto rt=helper(root->right);
    if(root->val>lt.maxi && root->val<rt.mini){
        int sum=root->val+lt.sum+rt.sum;
        ans=max(ans,sum);
        return BST(sum,min(root->val,lt.mini),max(root->val,rt.maxi));
    }
    return BST(max(lt.sum,rt.sum),INT_MIN,INT_MAX);
}
class Solution {
public:
    int maxSumBST(TreeNode* root) {
        ans=0;
        helper(root);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

