# Intuition
- We have to find global maximum sum of any BST present as subtree, so we will have to vist every node
- Each node has to calculate if node + subtree forms a BST or not. If yes, then global max Sum needs to be updated.
 - For processing at each node, we need to know if it forms a BST and if yes, then what is the sum.

# Approach
- First data point we need is if the node forms a BST, this is only possible if left subtree is a BST, right subtree is a BST and also the max of left subtree is less than node's data and min of right subtree is greater than node's data. We can easily see that we need 3 values from each subtree : isBST, max value and min value. With these value parent nodes can see if they are BST or not.
- If current node is not a BST we simply need to return to upper (parent) node only this info since nothing else is needed. However, if current node is a BST we need to pass 3 values talked in the previous point and also the sum of this current subtree. When we calculate sum of current BST subtree, we can also check to see if is max sum seen so far.
- This problem is like two easy problems combined: Check BST (check whether a tree is BST or not) and Tree Sum (calculate Sum). We just need to combine these logics and not return any other info if the current node does not form a BST since no other info is desired by parent node in this case.
- Since null node is also a BST, we return from it with default values.
- Since negative values are not to be taken and even empty BST is better than these, we start from maxSum as zero (rather than min integer possible in language).

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(n)$$ : We just need to traverse once

- Space complexity:
$$O(n)$$ : If the tree is highly skewed, then recursive calls on stack can take $$O(n)$$ space otherwise in a balnced tree, space complexity is $$O(log n)$$

# Code
```
class quad{     // 4 values have to be returned so made a quad class
    public :
    int maxEle;
    int minEle;
    bool isBST;
    int sum;
    quad(int maxEle, int minEle, bool isBST, int sum){
        this -> maxEle = maxEle;
        this -> minEle = minEle;
        this -> isBST = isBST;
        this -> sum = sum;
    }
    quad(){
        this-> isBST = false;       //when isBST is false, then other values can be garbage
    }
};
class Solution {
public:
    int maxSum = 0;
    quad traverse(TreeNode* root)
    {
        if(root == NULL)
            return quad(INT_MIN, INT_MAX, true, 0);

        quad leftAns = traverse(root ->left);
        quad rightAns = traverse(root -> right);

        bool isBST = leftAns.isBST && rightAns.isBST && (leftAns.maxEle < root->val) && (rightAns.minEle > root->val);

        if(!isBST)
            return quad();          // default constructor sets isBST to false, rest are garbage values
        else
            {
                int sum = leftAns.sum + rightAns.sum + root->val;
                if(sum > maxSum)            // try updating globally maintained sum
                    maxSum = sum;
                return quad(max(root->val, rightAns.maxEle),
                            min(root->val, leftAns.minEle),
                            true,
                            sum );
            }
    }
    int maxSumBST(TreeNode* root) {
        traverse(root);
        return maxSum;
    }
};
```

